  "pmid": "37490916",
  "doi": "10.1016/j.cell.2023.06.020",
  "title": "Targeting of multiple tumor-associated antigens by individual T cell receptors during successful cancer immunotherapy.",
  "journal": "Cell",
  "year": 2023,
  "authors": "Dolton G, Rius C, Wall A, Szomolay B, Bianchi V, Galloway SAE, Hasan MS, Morin T, Caillaud ME, Thomas HL, Theaker S, Tan LR, Fuller A, Topley K, Legut M, Attaf M, Hopkins JR, Behiry E, Zabkiewicz J, Alvares C, Lloyd A, Rogers A, Henley P, Fegan C, Ottmann O, Man S, Crowther MD, Donia M, Svane IM, Cole DK, Brown PE, Rizkallah P, Sewell AK."
 },
 "executive_summary": "Individual TCRs isolated from melanoma patients undergoing successful TIL therapy exhibited remarkable polyfunctionality, each recognizing three distinct HLA-A*02:01-restricted tumor-associated peptides: EAAGIGILTV (Melan A), LLLGIGILVL (BST2), and NLSALGIFST (IMP2). Crystal structures of the TCR bound to all three epitopes revealed a shared x-x-x-A/G-I/L-G-I-x-x-x recognition motif that enables this multi-epitope targeting. The ability of individual TCRs to simultaneously attack cancer through multiple tumor-associated antigens confers superior recognition of cancer cells compared to conventional single-epitope TCR recognition. This multipronged targeting strategy is significant for cancer immunotherapy development, as it suggests that engineering or selecting T cells capable of recognizing multiple tumor antigens could enhance therapeutic efficacy and potentially reduce tumor escape through antigen loss.",
